4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT GENERALLY REVISING JUDICIAL ELECTION LAWS;
5 PROVIDING FOR THE PARTISAN NOMINATION AND ELECTION OF SUPREME COURT JUSTICES,
6 DISTRICT COURT JUDGES, JUSTICES OF THE PEACE, AND MUNICIPAL COURT JUDGES; PROVIDING
7 THAT EACH VACANCY FOR A SUPREME COURT JUSTICE AND A DISTRICT COURT JUDGE IS A
8 SEPARATE AND INDEPENDENT OFFICE; ALLOWING JUDICIAL CANDIDATES TO ACCEPT
9 ENDORSEMENTS FROM POLITICAL PARTIES; ALLOWING POLITICAL PARTIES TO CONTRIBUTE TO
10 JUDICIAL CANDIDATES; PROVIDING THAT THE PROPOSED ACT BE SUBMITTED TO THE QUALIFIED
11 ELECTORS OF MONTANA; AMENDING SECTIONS 3-2-101, 3-5-201, 3-10-201, 3-10-206, 13-14-111, 13-14-
12 118, AND 13-37-211, MCA; REPEALING SECTIONS 13-14-211, 13-14-212, 13-14-213, AND 13-35-231, MCA;
13 AND PROVIDING AN APPLICABILITY DATE AND AN EFFECTIVE DATE.”
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
16
17 NEW SECTION. Section 1. Statement of purpose. It is the policy of the state of Montana that
18 candidates for district judges and supreme court justices must be nominated and elected on a partisan ballot in
19 the same manner as provided for other partisan offices. The chief justice of the supreme court shall assign an
20 individual number to each justice position and certify these numbers to the secretary of state. The clerk of
21 district court in a multijudge district shall certify department numbers assigned pursuant to state law to the
22 secretary of state. Joint fundraising committee expenditures supporting a judicial candidate are allowed even if
23 a participant is a political party committee.
24
